<subSubSection id="C36D29D9FFA0FFAA0C8CFE94FACFFE03" pageId="4" pageNumber="363" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BC87A52FFA0FFAA0C8CFE94FACFFE03" blockId="4.[151,1437,295,1150]" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0C8CFE94FEABFE7F" bold="true" box="[199,322,367,393]" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is superficially similar to the preceding new species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFA0FFAA0872FE8BFB5CFE7F" authorityName="Park &amp; Koo" authorityYear="2021" box="[1081,1205,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Viperinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orbiosus">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0872FE8BFB5CFE7F" box="[1081,1205,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">V. orbiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it can be easily distinguished by the male genitalia having different shape of the cucullus and the modified processes at each base of the valva: 1) the cucullus is narrowly elongated distally; 2) the process arising from the base of the valva has a broadened distal part, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFA0FFAA0E44FE27FD62FE03" authorityName="Park &amp; Koo" authorityYear="2021" box="[527,651,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Viperinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orbiosus">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0E44FE27FD62FE03" box="[527,651,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">V. orbiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is produced sharply with a pointed distal part. (
<figureCitation id="134C66D7FFA0FFAA08F4FE20FAF3FE03" box="[1215,1306,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1931,1955]" captionTargetBox="[182,1406,207,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[151,1436,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Viperinus pyknoistus Park &amp; Koo, sp. nov.: A: adult, holotype; B, ditto, dorsal surface of head; C, ditto, labial palpus; D, male genitalia, holotype, slide no. CIS-7490, with a close-up of uncus+juxta in different view; E, ditto, aedeagus; F, ditto, abdomen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4956114" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4956114/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36D29D9FFA0FFAA0C8CFE04FC64FBE7" pageId="4" pageNumber="363" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC87A52FFA0FFAA0C8CFE04FCF4FDEC" blockId="4.[151,1437,295,1150]" box="[199,797,511,538]" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0C8CFE04FEB0FDEF" bold="true" box="[199,345,511,537]" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Description.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation id="134C66D7FFA0FFAA0DE3FE04FDC1FDEF" box="[424,552,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1931,1955]" captionTargetBox="[182,1406,207,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[151,1436,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Viperinus pyknoistus Park &amp; Koo, sp. nov.: A: adult, holotype; B, ditto, dorsal surface of head; C, ditto, labial palpus; D, male genitalia, holotype, slide no. CIS-7490, with a close-up of uncus+juxta in different view; E, ditto, aedeagus; F, ditto, abdomen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4956114" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4956114/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Figs 2A–C</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 14.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC87A52FFA0FFAA0C8CFDD8FB6CFD5F" blockId="4.[151,1437,295,1150]" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0C8CFDD8FEEDFDCB" box="[199,260,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Head</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0D73FDD8FE60FDCB" box="[312,393,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Thorax</emphasis>
: No superficial characters separable from the preceding new species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFA0FFAA08C4FDDFFAE0FDCB" authorityName="Park &amp; Koo" authorityYear="2021" box="[1167,1289,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Viperinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orbiosus">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA08C4FDDFFAE0FDCB" box="[1167,1289,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">V. orbiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are found in the head, thorax and forewing color patterns. Only a little difference is observed in the 2 
<superScript id="7C02D71AFFA0FFAA083FFDBCFB6DFDA3" attach="left" box="[1140,1156,583,597]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">nd</superScript>
segment of labial palpus with dark brown in basal 1/3, then orange white in distal 2/3 on outer surface, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFA0FFAA08C3FD97FAEDFD73" authorityName="Park &amp; Koo" authorityYear="2021" box="[1160,1284,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Viperinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orbiosus">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA08C3FD97FAEDFD73" box="[1160,1284,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">V. orbiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it is covered with dark brown scales in basal 2/3, then gradually turning orange white on outer surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC87A52FFA0FFAA0C8CFD48FDE4FD07" blockId="4.[151,1437,295,1150]" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0C8CFD48FED8FD3B" box="[199,305,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Dark brown, spinose zones in a row along posterior margin of each dorsal segment, well accordant with that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C7701D1FFA0FFAA0D54FD23FE72FD07" authorityName="Park &amp; Koo" authorityYear="2021" box="[287,411,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Viperinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orbiosus">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0D54FD23FE72FD07" box="[287,411,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">V. orbiosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="134C66D7FFA0FFAA0DE0FD2CFDE9FD07" box="[427,512,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1931,1955]" captionTargetBox="[182,1406,207,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[151,1436,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Viperinus pyknoistus Park &amp; Koo, sp. nov.: A: adult, holotype; B, ditto, dorsal surface of head; C, ditto, labial palpus; D, male genitalia, holotype, slide no. CIS-7490, with a close-up of uncus+juxta in different view; E, ditto, aedeagus; F, ditto, abdomen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4956114" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4956114/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC87A52FFA0FFAA0C8CFD00FC64FBE7" blockId="4.[151,1437,295,1150]" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0C8CFD00FE87FCE3" box="[199,366,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="134C66D7FFA0FFAA0D35FD00FDE9FCE0" box="[382,512,763,790]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1931,1955]" captionTargetBox="[182,1406,207,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[151,1436,181,1908]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Viperinus pyknoistus Park &amp; Koo, sp. nov.: A: adult, holotype; B, ditto, dorsal surface of head; C, ditto, labial palpus; D, male genitalia, holotype, slide no. CIS-7490, with a close-up of uncus+juxta in different view; E, ditto, aedeagus; F, ditto, abdomen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4956114" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4956114/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Figs 2D, E</figureCitation>
): Uncus broad basally, gradually narrowed distally, with round apex. Basal plate of gnathos produced distally, nearly pentagon; median process small, strongly bent downwardly beyond 5/6. Tegumen deeply concave in wide inverted V-shaped, heavily sclerotized on anterior margin. Valva with short basal part; slightly expanded dorsally near base of costa; cucullus long, narrowly elongated distally; ventral margin nearly straight, arched medially; apex narrowly produced; a pair of large, unique, arched processes arising one from each base of valva, broadened apically, giraffe ossicone-shaped, with dense setae. Juxta weakly developed. Aedeagus nearly same length as valva, narrow in basal 2/5, distal 3/5 broadened, with semi-ovate ventral lobe, sharply produced ventrally; dorsal margin heavily sclerotized; cornutus absent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
