</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36D29D9FFA0FFAA0C8CFBC4FD3AFB88" pageId="4" pageNumber="363" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BC87A52FFA0FFAA0C8CFBC4FD3AFB88" blockId="4.[151,1437,295,1150]" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0C8CFBC4FEA7FBAF" bold="true" box="[199,334,1087,1113]" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is derived from the Greek, 
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0F0FFBC4FC7BFBAF" box="[836,914,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">pyknos</emphasis>
(= thick) with Greek superlative ending, - 
<emphasis id="B903A640FFA0FFAA0929FBBBFA7CFBAF" box="[1378,1429,1088,1113]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="363">istus</emphasis>
, referring to the thickened flagellum of the antenna.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
